'''Surfactant leaching''' is a method of water and [[soil decontamination]],<ref name=ebpa>''Environmental Biotechnology: Principles and Applications'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=aCDtCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA272 p. 272]</ref> <ref name=kbl>Knudsen O. Ø., P.J. Brandvik, A. Lewis, "Treating oil spills with W/O emulsion inhibitors: A laboratory study of surfactant leaching from the oil to the water phase", in: Proceedings of the Seventeenth Arctic and Marine Oilspill Program Technical Seminar, 1994, pp. 1023-1034 </ref> e.g., for [[Oil spill|oil recovery]] in [[petroleum industry]].<ref name=hcs>''Hydrocarbon Contaminated Soils'', Volume 3, [https://books.google.com/books?id=K0PNgljP75wC&pg=PA16 pp. 15,16]</ref><ref name=kbl/> It involves mixing of contaminated water or soil with [[surfactant]]s with the subsequent [[leaching (chemistry)|leaching]] of [[emulsification|emulsified]] contaminants.<ref name=ebpa/><ref name=hcs/> In oil recovery, most common surfactant types are [[ethoxylated alcohol]]s, [[ethoxylated nonylphenol]]s, [[sulphate]]s, [[sulphonate]]s, and biosurfactants.<ref name=hcs/>
==References== {{reflist}}
